# Powerhouse Workflow

Single integrated workflow for AI-first engineering. Ref: [Cursor Rules](https://cursor.com/docs/context/rules), [GSD](https://github.com/gsd-build/get-shit-done), [Spec Kit](https://github.com/github/spec-kit), [BMAD](https://github.com/bmad-code-org/BMAD-METHOD).

## Pipeline (artifact handoffs)

1. **Constitution** → principles and constraints (see `docs/constitution.md`).
2. **Product/PRD** → what we build and why (see `docs/prd.template.md`).
3. **Architecture** → how it fits together (see `docs/architecture.template.md`, `docs/adr/`).
4. **Tasks** → atomic, ordered work items (see `planning/tasks.template.md`).
5. **Implement** → code changes with atomic commits.
6. **Verify/UAT** → tests, lint, typecheck, build; then human acceptance.

Do not skip upstream artifacts: e.g. do not implement from a vague idea without at least a minimal spec or task list. If in doubt, create a one-paragraph spec first.

## Modes

Pick one per session. Steps and rigor scale by mode.

| Mode | When to use | Spec/PRD | Architecture | Task breakdown | Verification |
|------|-------------|----------|--------------|----------------|--------------|
| **Quick fix** | Bug, config tweak, tiny change | No | No | Optional (one task) | Run verify script |
| **Feature** | New capability, bounded scope | Minimal (acceptance criteria) | Reference existing ADRs | Yes | Verify + UAT checklist |
| **Refactor** | Restructure without changing behavior | No | ADR if structural | Yes (per area) | Verify; tests must pass |
| **Greenfield** | New project or major subsystem | Full PRD | Architecture doc + ADRs | Yes | Full verify + UAT |
| **Brownfield** | Add to or change existing codebase | Align to existing docs | Map first; then ADR for changes | Yes | Verify; regression tests |

- **Quick fix**: Do the change. Run `./scripts/verify.sh` (or equivalent). Commit with conventional message. If verification fails, fix before committing.
- **Feature / Refactor / Greenfield / Brownfield**: Follow the mandatory checklist for that mode (below). Reference `@specs-and-planning.mdc` for templates.

## Mandatory checklists per mode

### Quick fix
- [ ] Change is localized (single concern).
- [ ] Run verification: `./scripts/verify.sh` (or project equivalent).
- [ ] Commit: type `fix` or `chore`, scope optional. Ref: [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/).

### Feature
- [ ] Acceptance criteria written (in PRD snippet or task doc); testable.
- [ ] Tasks listed in `planning/` (or equivalent); each task has a verification step.
- [ ] Implementation: one logical change per commit; use `feat(scope):` or `fix(scope):`.
- [ ] Run verification; fix any failure before marking done.
- [ ] UAT: confirm acceptance criteria with human check or automated test.

### Refactor
- [ ] ADR created if the refactor changes architecture or boundaries (see `docs/adr/0001-template.md`).
- [ ] Task list covers refactor areas; order respects dependencies.
- [ ] Tests exist for affected behavior; run verify; no behavior change except structure.

### Greenfield
- [ ] Constitution (or principles) in `docs/constitution.md`.
- [ ] PRD (or minimal product spec) in `docs/`; scope and success criteria clear.
- [ ] Architecture doc + at least one ADR for key decisions.
- [ ] Task breakdown in `planning/`; then implement in order; verify each step.

### Brownfield
- [ ] Map existing code (readme, key modules, entrypoints); note where change touches.
- [ ] Update or create PRD/spec slice for the new work; align with existing architecture.
- [ ] ADR for any new architectural decision.
- [ ] Task breakdown; implement; run verify; regression check.

## Verification commands

- **Default (script)**: Run `./scripts/verify.sh`. It should run (in order): lint → test → typecheck → build. If the project has no stack yet, the script may contain TODO blocks—replace with real commands.
- **Manual (if no script)**: Run in order: lint → tests → typecheck (if applicable) → build. Do not commit with failing verification unless explicitly documenting a known broken state (e.g. WIP branch).
- **Per-task**: Each task in `planning/tasks.*` should state how to verify it (e.g. "Run `npm test -- --grep 'auth'`" or "Build and open /settings").

## Regeneration over patching drift

When spec and implementation have drifted: **prefer regenerating from the spec** over endless local patches. (1) Update spec to desired behavior. (2) Regenerate or reimplement the affected slice. (3) Run verify and fix regressions. Ref: [intent-driven SDD](https://intent-driven.dev/knowledge/best-practices/).

## Atomic commit format

- **One logical change per commit.** Ref: [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/). Format: `type(scope): short description`. Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`. Breaking: `!` or footer `BREAKING CHANGE:`. Do not mix unrelated edits. Ref: GSD atomic commits.

## Security (mandatory)

- **Secrets**: Never commit secrets, API keys, or credentials. Do not read sensitive paths into prompts unless redacted.
- **Secret deny patterns** (deny read in Cursor/IDE): `.env`, `.env.*`, `!.env.example`; `**/secrets/*`, `**/*credential*`, `**/*.pem`, `**/*.key`; any path with API keys/tokens. Ref: GSD security.
- **Denylist**: Prefer denying read access to sensitive paths in your environment over relying on “don’t paste” alone.
- **Safe file access**: Do not write outside project root; do not overwrite ignored or protected files (e.g. listed in .cursorignore or .gitignore for good reason) without explicit user request.

## When NOT to use this

- Exploratory spikes or throwaway prototypes: use quick fix or a single “spike” task; skip full PRD/architecture.
- Copy-paste or one-off scripts: no need for PRD or ADR; still run verify if the repo has a verify script.
- Documentation-only changes: use `docs:` commit type; no task breakdown required unless it’s a large doc set.
